post_text:
Viking Family:

It is with deep regret and sadness that I am informing you about a recent loss to our Viking Community.

USD 330 Mission Valley was notified this morning that Ryah Brown passed away at her home sometime during the night. Ryah was a proud 2019 Viking graduate of Mission Valley and was continuing her Mission Valley education working in the 18-21 program.

We are shocked and saddened by this tragic event and our counseling staff will be available to provide support in this time of loss to anyone in our school community. If you have any concerns regarding your child's reaction to this loss, please contact the school so that we can provide assistance and support.

USD 330 Mission Valley will provide information regarding services at a later date. Thank you for your support as we move forward. Ryah will truly be missed by her friends and staff members at Mission Valley. Our thoughts go out to the family during this time of loss and grief.

Sincerely,

William J. Clark

USD 330 Mission Valley

Superintendent/Director of Special Services

post_text: PSAT/NMSQT Assessment is being held on 10/14/2020 from 8:15-11:30 a.m. This assessment does have scholarship opportunities available for those that score well. This assessment is focused on sophomores, but juniors/seniors can take it as well. Cost is $16, waivers are available. A sign up sheet will be put up next to the counselor's office on 9/4/2020. Slots are limited, so if you would like your child to take this assessment please have them sign up starting 9/4/2020. The more assessments taken, of this type/fashion, will only better prepare them to increase their ACT or SAT scores. Higher ACT/SAT scores increase chances for ease of admission, scholarship opportunities, and the possibility of not having to take some lower lever prerequisite college classes (saves money & time). If you have any questions, please contact Mr. Hancock at jhancock@mv330.org or 866-557-6686 ext 230.

post_text:
FCCLA “Masking” A Difference

This month, FCCLA members came together to help make personal masks for all of the staff members. Emma Slade and Clara Johnson were rockstars at the sewing machines while the other participating members (Paige Sims, KikiWidau, Megan Deters Karlyn Gustin and Athena White) organized, measured, cut, and ironed the fabric. This
project took several days to complete but was well worth it to see all of the staff members wearing handmade masks to keep them safe! FCCLA made a total of 82 staff masks in all. We would like to thank Toni Steere from “A Wing and a Prayer Designs” for the generous fabric donation!

To continue to show our appreciation for teachers, FCCLA members came into the school right before school began to help them set up, decorate and organize their rooms so they would be ready for the first day! Through two days of work, the members helped 17 teachers and staff members and they were so thankful for the help.

Thank you MV Teachers for all you do!

By: Megan Deters, VP of Public Relations

post_text:
5th & 6th Grade Families,

As we are quickly approaching our first day of school, I wanted to make you aware of a couple changes to our elementary band program.

5th Grade
Instead of students choosing an instrument and sticking with it for the year, all 5th grade students will be given the opportunity to try different instruments through the year. To avoid having 30-40 students in one room at a time, students will rotate in small groups to band throughout the week so Mrs. Sperry can give more attention to our beginning learners.

6th grade
Band will be optional for 6th grade students. If students choose to participate, they will be put in small groups and rotate throughout the week to allow for more small group attention. All 6th grade students will still receive general music.

If you have any questions, please don't hesitate to reach out to me (ajohnston@mv330.org) or Mrs. Sperry (ksperry@mv330.org). We are both excited for this change!

Amy Johnston
Elementary Principal
USD 330 Mission Valley

post_text:
We have made the decision to cancel all sports related (KSHSAA) activities at the school next week. We are going to take (1) week off to evaluate how we are operating, discuss any changes or modifications that we want to do, monitor the health and wellness of students as they return from July 4th weekend, etc... This decision is NOT due to any student or staff testing positive or being exposed to anyone with COVID-19. In addition, the basketball coaches have cancelled their summer workouts with their players for the remainder of the summer. The decision to cancel basketball workouts was made by the coaches and was highly supported by administration. I greatly appreciate their decision.

We will continue as planned with Drivers Education and Extended School Year services for students with significant disabilities. We will follow the guidance from Wabaunsee County Health Department regarding maintaining 6 ft distance and if 6 ft distance can not be maintained then staff will wear masks. In addition we will also stress handwashing, sanitization, etc.

Tomorrow is the Viking Voyage for our Graduating Seniors. We will leave MV at 11:45 a.m. and travel east on MV Road, then turn south on Harveyville Rd and go down mainstreet of Harveyville. We will turn west on K-31 and then turn north on K-99 to Eskridge. In Eskridge we will turn "north" on main street onto K-4 and travel to Dover. From Dover we will turn south onto Douglas/Crawford to 89th. On 89th we will turn back west and return to Mission Valley via Harveville Rd and MV Rd.

We plan to arrive in Harveyville at approximately 12:00, Eskridge at 12:30 and Dover at 1:00.

Our "Voyage" will consist of Wab Co Sheriff, Local Fire Dept, Admin, Graduates, MV Faculty/Staff, Local Fire Dept, and Sheriff Dept.

We would love for everyone to participate either in the "Voyage" or along the Route! Go Vikings!

COVID-19 Update

March 18, 2020

The KSHSAA is committed to the safety of our student-participants and the health of our school communities. Accordingly, in response to Governor Kelly’s Executive Order regarding the closure and cessation of in-person instruction in all Kansas schools through May 29, 2020, the KSHSAA is cancelling all spring championships, competitions, and festivals for the remainder of this school year. The KSHSAA recognizes the value of school activities for all students and school communities, but the current situation does not permit the opportunity for school activities to take place in a manner that is consistent with the very reason school activities exist....https://5il.co/dwxf

post_text:
This week we celebrate Public Schools Week where Public Schools educate over 50.8 million students who learn from more than 3.2 million teachers and support staff. Public schools open their doors to every child regardless of their abilities, race, wealth, language, or country of origin. Strong Public Schools build the knowledge and skills young people need to be successful in the future.

We at Mission Valley are proud to provide our students the opportunity to be involved in the Arts (Art, Music, Drama, Forensics, Photography, etc.), Athletics, Daily Physical Education, FFA, FCCLA, KAY, SADD, Extra-Curricular activities such as Book Clubs, Gaming Club, etc), Community Service activities such as Viking Leaders, and many more.

Please join us in support of Public Schools!

"Learning is a treasure that will follow its owner everywhere." -Chinese Proverb

post_text:
February 3-7 is designated as School Counseling Week and highlights the impact they have in helping students achieve success.

Did you know that in the last two years the number of school counselors has increased from 1,167 counselors to 1,299 in Kansas?

With the emphasis on Social and Emotional well being counselors encourage and support students to make good choices. In addition, they focus on academics and help assist in student career development.
We are thankful for Jamey Hancock, Katie Burnett and Mary Masilionis for their support and encouragement in helping our students succeed! Thank You!

post_text:
The HS will be taking a Pep Bus to the games on Friday afternoon. Students need to have a permission slip turned into the office by 9:00 am on Friday morning.

Mr. Johnson MUST HAVE THE SIGNED SHEET. You will not be able to ride the bus if you try and have a parent call in on Friday. If you ride the pep bus you are required to ride the bus back to Mission Valley and will not be allowed to ride home with another student or other parents.

If you ride the pep bus your attendance will be counted as a school activity. The school is sponsoring the opportunity. IF you choose to have your parents call in and excuse you to go to the game it will count as an excused absence, but is not exempt.

Remember, the Pep Bus will be leaving at 1:30 p.m. you will need $3.00 for admission to the game and then any extra money for concessions. The bus will not stop on the way back.

THEME is "VIKING NATION" come dressed in the Crimson and GOLD

post_text:
Hello Vikings,

This week we have two basketball games.

Tuesday 1/14, we play Northern Heights at home. Mission Valley students and fans find your inner Cowboy and come to the game dressed up as cowboys, some ideas to dress up are cowboy hats, boots jeans, belts.

Friday we travel to West Franklin. The theme for that game is White Out, wear all white clothes! Let’s show some Viking pride!!

Go Vikes!

post_text: As school let out today we were amazed and thankful for a couple of our High School students who were roaming the parking lot clearing ice covered car windows. Although they were dressed for their games tonight, we thank Dawson Logan and Justice Dunbar for going above and beyond and are thankful for their kind act.
